    <item>
      <title>Chart: How much is your local chief constable paid?</title>
      <link>/post/police-chief-pay/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 16 Mar 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>/post/police-chief-pay/</guid>
      <description>


&lt;p&gt;Most police pay is set on a national scale, but police and crime commissioners can vary pay for chief officers. This leads to big differences across the country: the Hampshire chief constable is paid £62k more than the Avon &amp;amp; Somerset chief, despite the two forces being very similar in size.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;/post/police-chief-pay_files/figure-html/display%20plot-1.png&#34; width=&#34;672&#34; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;../police-chief-pay.png&#34;&gt;larger image&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/mpjashby/lesscrime.info/blob/master/content/post/police-chief-pay.Rmd&#34;&gt;annotated R code to produce this chart&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Data source: &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/police_chief_officer_renumeratio&#34;&gt;Home Office, 2020&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id=&#34;notes&#34; class=&#34;section level3&#34;&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Notes&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The line shown in the chart is produced by a linear regression model that uses the number of officers in a police force to predict the renumeration of the chief constable, then identifies the difference between that prediction and the actual renumeration received. The regression model can be summarised as:&lt;/p&gt;
